{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491186"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:36:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"862"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/862"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.31,0.08,0.14,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111279"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/862"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93411"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7965"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38230"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44335"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111279"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner complaining of a new skin lesion which has developed over the last week. When it first appeared it looked like a small red lump, but over the last few days it has enlarged and looked a bit like a blister before he accidentally knocked off the top at work yesterday. He reports some tenderness at the site, with associated erythema. He reports no other skin rashes or lumps. He denies systemic symptoms such as chills, rigors or malaise. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes which is well controlled on metformin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the following lesion is identified over the dorsal aspect of his right hand (Image). It is tender to palpation with minimal discharge.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the patient\u0027s most likely occupation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Snake handler","Sheep shearer","Fisherman","Electrician","Gardener"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe above lesion is characteristic orf, also known as contagious pustular dermatitis. Orf virus (ORFV), a aparapoxvirus, is a zoonotic skin infection caused by a parapoxvirus and is acquired through direct contact with sheep or goats, typically via minor hand abrasions. It is an occupational hazard for people who work with these animals including \u003Cstrong\u003Esheep shearers\u003C/strong\u003E, veterinarians, abattoir workers and butchers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lesion usually appears on the dorsal hands or fingers and evolves through recognisable stages over 3\u20136 weeks: a red papule emerges about a week after contact, often with local tenderness; it enlarges to 2\u20135 cm with concentric rings of white and red around a central red area; it then forms a blood, pus or fluid-filled blister that may weep and bleed easily; a dry crust develops; and finally a warty, papillomatous appearance ensues before healing. Mild fever and malaise can occur early, and red streaking along lymphatic channels with tender regional lymph nodes may be present. The diagnosis of orf is clinical, considering the typical appearance and progression of the lesion and exposures of the patient to goats or sheep. Management is supportive with wound care, as it usually resolves without specific antiviral therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDifferential diagnoses includes pyogenic granuloma and atypical mycobacterial infection. This is a diagnosis which is made based on appearance and history provided by the patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Orf is a zoonotic infection, typically transmitted by sheep."],"references":["Bergqvist C, Kurban M, Abbas O. Orf virus infection. Reviews in Medical Virology. 2017;27(4):e1932.","Vun Y. Orf. In: The Australian College of Dermatologists A to Z of Skin [online]. Cited 2025 Aug 12. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Orf-A-Z-of-Skin.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93411"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"862"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16811"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16811"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/02866f21-7047-4d5c-b43b-ebe7229293d0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/02866f21-7047-4d5c-b43b-ebe7229293d0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":561,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93411"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T08:46:0